TI  - Contrastive adversarial tuning: Enhancing discriminability and robustness of LLMs for emotion recognition in conversation
PY  - 2026
T2  - Pattern Recognition
VL  - 174
C7  - 113025
DO  - 10.1016/j.patcog.2025.113025
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105028267361&doi=10.1016%2Fj.patcog.2025.113025&partnerID=40&md5=91af1747c7b922f28b2f54fede0dfa0d
AB  - With the rapid development of large language models (LLMs), LLM-based approaches to emotion recognition in conversation (ERC) have achieved substantial improvements by leveraging long-range context modeling. However, the feature representations produced by LLMs often lack clear class separability because their pre-training objectives prioritize semantic coherence over discriminative emotion boundaries, making them sensitive to fine-grained overlap and conversational perturbations. To overcome these limitations, we investigate enhancing class discriminability via representation optimization and strengthening robustness through distributional perturbations. Building on these insights, we cast ERC as a conditional generation problem and propose a novel fine-tuning framework, Contrastive Adversarial Tuning (CAT). Furthermore, two complementary mechanisms are designed to enhance representation discriminability and robustness: (1) context-based contrastive learning, which increases intra-class compactness and inter-class separability; and (2) distribution-based adversarial training, which enlarges decision margins and enforces prediction stability under noisy conditions. Experimental results on ERC benchmarks across multiple LLM backbones demonstrate that CAT achieves state-of-the-art performance, delivering clearer separation of similar emotions and stronger robustness to input perturbations. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd
