AB  - Alzheimer’s disease (AD) remains the predominant cause of dementia worldwide and ranks among the leading causes of mortality due to its progressive neurodegenerative nature. Early diagnosis of AD, particularly during the preclinical and mild cognitive impairment (MCI) stages, is critical for enabling timely interventions and improving patient outcomes. This systematic review comprehensively examines deep learning-based approaches for AD prediction, emphasizing the integration of multimodal datasets—including neuroimaging (MRI and PET scans), genetic biomarkers (e.g., SNPs, APOE genotypes), and clinical cognitive assessments. Recent advances reveal that multimodal fusion techniques significantly enhance model performance by capturing complementary structural, functional, and molecular features of disease progression. Architectures employing convolutional neural networks (CNNs), recurrent neural networks (RNNs), transformers, and graph-based models are critically analyzed, alongside various fusion strategies such as intermediate, late, attention-based, and graph-based fusion. The review also highlights current limitations, including over-reliance on the ADNI dataset, challenges in handling missing modalities, limited model interpretability, and gaps in external validation. Emerging trends point toward the adoption of federated learning, contrastive learning, explainable AI (XAI), and scalable multimodal frameworks to bridge these gaps. In conclusion, deep learning frameworks leveraging heterogeneous biomarkers represent a transformative frontier in proactive AD diagnosis and personalized disease management, yet real-world clinical translation demands concerted efforts in model robustness, generalizability, and ethical AI deployment. © 2025 NIPES Pub.
